{"id": "6964", "revid": "49243392", "url": "https://darksouls.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6964", "title": "Gestures", "text": "Gestures are used by players to communicate with one another in \"&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls\"&gt;Dark Souls&lt;/a&gt;\". In the absence of having a voice-chat option, gestures and\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Carvings\"&gt;Carvings&lt;/a&gt;, with the addition of\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Artorias%20of%20the%20Abyss\"&gt;Artorias of the Abyss&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0DLC,\u00a0are the only way to directly communicate with another player short of sending a message.\nGeneral information.\nFor practical purposes, gestures can be used by players to indicate to one another the right direction or action to take when at a junction. Gestures are more commonly used to indicate emotions, as well as for taunting.\nGestures require time to perform. During this time, the player is as vulnerable to attacks as if they were standing still. Gestures can only be cancelled by initiating another gesture, or being attacked. Therefore, it's best to perform gestures out of harm's way. (As of Dark Souls 3, gestures can be cancelled by performing any action or pressing any button and do not have to be completed)."}
{"id": "62994", "revid": "49243392", "url": "https://darksouls.fandom.com/wiki?curid=62994", "title": "Gestures (Dark Souls II)", "text": "Gestures are player actions in \"&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls%20II\"&gt;Dark Souls II&lt;/a&gt;\".\u00a0A few are received at the start of the game, and more are taught by certain NPCs throughout the game. Usually to learn the gesture one has to exhaust all dialogue with the NPC.\nUnlike the first \"Dark Souls\", players can cancel out of a gesture's animation by rolling or backstepping.\nLearning all 20 gestures unlocks the &lt;a href=\"Achievements/Trophies%20%28Dark%20Souls%20II%29\"&gt;Achievement/Trophy&lt;/a&gt; \"Gesture Maestro\", worth 50 Gamerscore or a Silver Trophy respectively."}
{"id": "132872", "revid": "49243392", "url": "https://darksouls.fandom.com/wiki?curid=132872", "title": "Gestures (Dark Souls III)", "text": "Gestures are a in \"&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls%20III\"&gt;Dark Souls III&lt;/a&gt;\".\nDescription.\nGestures are special animations the player can perform, often used as a means of communicating with other players. Among other things, gestures can be used to greet another player, thank them or making them aware of a nearby treasure.\nThe player starts the game with several gestures already at their disposal. These can be consulted and managed by pressing the button, bringing up a list with seven gestures ready for use. To perform a gesture, select it and press the action button ( / ) or / .\nAs more gestures are learned, the player can press / to open a complete menu of all the player's collected gestures. From here, gestures can either be added to the quick menu by selecting them or used directly by pressing / .\nAdditional gestures can be learned throughout the course of the game. These are usually learned from other , after performing certain actions, or after defeating certain enemies.\nThere are a total of 33 gestures to be obtained in the game."}
{"id": "2292", "revid": "49243392", "url": "https://darksouls.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2292", "title": "Ghost", "text": "Ghosts are special in \"&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls\"&gt;Dark Souls&lt;/a&gt;\". They are invulnerable to a player who is not &lt;a href=\"Curse%20%28Dark%20Souls%29\"&gt;Cursed&lt;/a&gt;.\nLocation.\nGhosts can be found in &lt;a href=\"New%20Londo%20Ruins\"&gt;New Londo Ruins&lt;/a&gt;.\nStrategy.\nStay on the move and evade, as the Ghost's attacks are difficult to block. In particular, they may stretch their arms out and attack from behind. The player must stay alert as they explore the ruins, as ghosts can pass through any solid object, enabling them to attack through the floors, walls and even the ceilings. It is even possible for them to go through the fogwall leading to the boss in the area, so it is advised to either deal with them or dropping into the Abyss as quickly as possible as they will not follow the player there.\nGhosts stagger easily. Using a high-powered weapon can prove effective.\nCurse.\nLike the &lt;a href=\"Banshee\"&gt;Banshee&lt;/a&gt;, Ghosts can only be killed if the player is &lt;a href=\"Curse%20%28Dark%20Souls%29\"&gt;Cursed&lt;/a&gt; or if they're carrying a cursed weapon. &lt;a href=\"Transient%20Curse\"&gt;Transient Curse&lt;/a&gt; allows temporary contact with Ghosts and Banshees without actually being cursed. It acts as a &lt;a href=\"Self%20Augmentation\"&gt;self augmentation&lt;/a&gt; effect and will prevent the use of other self augmentations, such as regeneration effects for health and stamina.\nIf the player is not cursed, they will not be able to interact with the Ghost in any way. This includes damaging it, of course, but also blocking it or just reducing the damage taken with armor. Furthermore, the Ghost's attacks will always stagger the player when not cursed, as they'll bypass armor, leaving the player &lt;a href=\"Poise%20%28Dark%20Souls%29\"&gt;poiseless&lt;/a&gt;.\nPlayers can also use cursed weapons (such as the &lt;a href=\"Jagged%20Ghost%20Blade\"&gt;Jagged Ghost Blade&lt;/a&gt; or the &lt;a href=\"Greatsword%20of%20Artorias%20%28Cursed%29\"&gt;Cursed Greatsword of Artorias&lt;/a&gt;). While this allows contact with the Ghost, it will still leave the player unable to block with a shield or reduce damage taken with armor. Cursed weapons can also be used to block.\nIf possible, the most complete strategy is to use a Transient Curse but still use a cursed weapon. This makes it so that the player is not left completely defenseless, should the Transient Curse lose its effect at a bad time, or without the player noticing.\nLore.\nThey are the ghosts of the people who once inhabited New Londo, but were sacrificed when New Londo was flooded to contain the &lt;a href=\"Darkwraith%20%28enemy%29\"&gt;Darkwraiths&lt;/a&gt;. Their physical remains can be found at the big gate entrance leading to the &lt;a href=\"Valley%20of%20Drakes\"&gt;Valley of Drakes&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "3263", "revid": "56333033", "url": "https://darksouls.fandom.com/wiki?curid=3263", "title": "Ghost Blade", "text": "The Ghost Blade is a &lt;a href=\"Daggers\"&gt;dagger&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls\"&gt;Dark Souls&lt;/a&gt;\".\nAvailability.\n1% drop from the &lt;a href=\"Banshee\"&gt;Banshee&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"New%20Londo%20Ruins\"&gt;New Londo Ruins&lt;/a&gt;. \nCharacteristics.\nGhost Blade has the rare &lt;a href=\"Curse%20%28auxiliary%20effect%29\"&gt;curse&lt;/a&gt; effect, meaning it can innately damage Ghosts and when used two-handed can block their attacks without needing a &lt;a href=\"Transient%20Curse\"&gt;Transient Curse&lt;/a&gt; while going through &lt;a href=\"New%20Londo%20Ruins\"&gt;New Londo Ruins&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe Ghost Blade has the highest base damage of all the daggers, however, it cannot be &lt;a href=\"Weapon%20Augmentation\"&gt;buffed&lt;/a&gt;, does not cause &lt;a href=\"Bleed%20%28Dark%20Souls%29\"&gt;Bleed&lt;/a&gt;, and has the second lowest (although still significant) critical modifier of all daggers. Although it is listed as a slashing and thrusting weapon, almost the entirety of its &lt;a href=\"moveset\"&gt;moveset&lt;/a&gt; uses &lt;a href=\"Slash%20%28Damage%20Type%29\"&gt;slash&lt;/a&gt; attacks."}
{"id": "132532", "revid": "49243392", "url": "https://darksouls.fandom.com/wiki?curid=132532", "title": "Ghru", "text": "Ghrus are &lt;a href=\"Enemies%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;enemies&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls%20III\"&gt;Dark Souls III&lt;/a&gt;\".\nDescription.\nA strange race of creatures resembling bestial satyrs, Ghru are tribal warriors that make their home deep within the swamps of &lt;a href=\"Farron%20Keep\"&gt;Farron Keep&lt;/a&gt;. Despite their bestial appearance, they possess limited intelligence, utilizing weapons and &lt;a href=\"Poison%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;poisons&lt;/a&gt; in combat.\nThe Ghru are one of the most varied enemy types in the game with five different variations encountered. Stronger versions, known as &lt;a href=\"Smouldering%20Ghru\"&gt;Smouldering Ghru&lt;/a&gt;, are found in the &lt;a href=\"Smouldering%20Lake\"&gt;Smouldering Lake&lt;/a&gt;. They fight in the same way as their regular variants, although they can also inflict &lt;a href=\"Toxic%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;Toxic&lt;/a&gt; on the player.\nStrategy.\nStandard Ghru and their variants are some of the most difficult non-&lt;a href=\"Boss%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;boss&lt;/a&gt; enemies in the game. They have a decent range of aggro and can close on a player quickly, with several different attacks. Those that are armed can do so with a larger reach, save for the variants wielding a spear and shield, which possess the standard thrust and swipe attack.\nUnarmed Ghru are to be considered the most dangerous as they have a very well telegraphed, yet highly tracking grab attack. That can nearly kill most players, especially on their first play though and will most likely kill them on &lt;a href=\"NG%2B%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;NG+&lt;/a&gt;. The grab attack will also buff the Ghru in return and empower their attacks and even apply a slight attack speed increase as well. Though &lt;a href=\"Poise%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;poise&lt;/a&gt; remains unaffected in the exchange. &lt;a href=\"Stun-lock\"&gt;Stun-lock&lt;/a&gt;ing the Ghru is preferable to a straight up melee fight. As they can easily do the same with either one of their combos. This is doubly so for the unarmed variants, as the attacks track at a moderate pace and the Ghru travels forward with each attack. Allowing it to pursue the player as they are knocked backwards from each strike."}
